soldiers expressing objection to the war.Rebecca Ayako Bennette argues that the treatment of these soldiers was far less dismissive of real ailments and more conducive to individual expression of protest than we have previously thought. In addition, Diagnosing Dissent provides an important reevaluation of German psychiatry during this period. Bennette's argument fundamentally changes how we interpret central issues such as the strength of the German Rechtsstaat and the continuities or discontinuities between the events of World War I and the atrocities committed—often in the name of medicine and sometimes by the same physicians—during World War II.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary psychiatryzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSoldierszGermanyxPsychology. 0aWar neuroseszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xConscientious objectorszGermanyxPsychology. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xDesertionszGermanyxPsychological aspects. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xPsychological aspects. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aWorld War I. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh  aShell shock, military psychiatry, World War I, Hysteria, Dissent, peace studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501751226?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501751226423Coveruhttps://w